HEADWORD: Ewer
<hw>Ew"er</hw> <pr>(⟦umac⟧"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>ewer</ets>, <ets>euwier</ets>, prop. a water carrier, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧vier</ets> a washing place, sink,
<ets>aigui⟦egrave⟧re</ets> ewer, L. <ets>aquarius</ets>, adj., water
carrying, n., a water carrier, fr. <ets>aqua</ets> water; akin to Goth.
<ets>ahwa</ets> water, river, OHG. <ets>aha</ets>, G. <ets>au</ets>,
<ets>aue</ets>, meadow. ⟦root⟧219. Cf. <er>Aquarium</er>,
<er>Aquatic</er>, <er>Island</er>.]</ety> <def>A kind of wide-mouthed
pitcher or jug; esp., one used to hold water for the toilet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Basins and <qex>ewers</qex> to lave her dainty hands.</q>
